    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-08-20T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-08-20T13:00:00-05:00" n="550"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d550">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">867N.01/8–2048: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Special Representative of the United States in Israel</hi>
                        (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">McDonald</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">us urgent</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tel Aviv</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-08-20T22:00:00+04:00"
                            >August 20, 1948—10 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>63. At official reception for me and staff today I had 45 minute confidential
                    conversation with Ben-Gurion. I took occasion to emphasize danger if <gloss
                        target="#t_PGI1">PGI</gloss> should have illusion that the USA would under
                    no circumstances participate in imposition of sanctions. I added that conditions
                    might rise wherein US sense of justice and right would, despite US deep
                    friendship for Israel, lead to such action.<note n="1" xml:id="d550fn1">After
                        his discussion with the Israeli Prime Minister, Mr. McDonald repeated the
                        same point of view to Mr. Shertok, who made no special comment (telegram 64,
                        August 20, 6 p. m., from Tel Aviv, 867N.01/8–2048).</note>
                </p>
                <p>Ben-Gurion appeared to appreciate friendliness of my frankness He replied,
                    however, that there were two points on which Israel would never compromise (1)
                    the independence of state, and (2) any action involving threat to national
                    security. As regards point (2) he was at moment referring to danger of allowing
                    mass return Arab refugees prior to peace.</p>
                <p>I made no comment on Prime Minister’s dictum, but my view concurred in by my
                    staff, is <gloss target="#t_PGI1">PGI</gloss> cannot from military standpoint
                    now allow mass return refugees within small confines state, thus creating danger
                    of having enemy at back as well as in front.</p>
                <p>I must also add that I believe <gloss target="#t_PGI1">PGI</gloss>, suicidal
                    though such policy might seem, would under conceivable circumstances resist UN
                    sanctions rather than compromise on either of above two points.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">McDonald</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
